Update on dinoflagellates: Concentration is reduced in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fisheries and Wildlife Commission (FWC) shows a general reduction in the concentration of dinoflagellates in the area around Tampa Bay.
According to the FWC, uneven conditions for growth are reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and the county around Collier – suggesting a reduction in concentration.
A growth of dinoflagellates spreads beyond about 200 km on the coastline from northern Pinellas to the southern counties of Lee.
Areas with dinoflagellates are found about 16 km off the coast at Hillsborough, but compared to last week there are fewer areas.
Dinoflagellates have and have been observed in Pasco.
There have been reports of medium concentration in Pinellas in the past week, low to high concentration along the coast in Hillsborough, low concentration in Manatee, high concentration along the coast in Sarasota, medium concentration in Charlotte, high concentration in Lee and low concentration in Collier.
Irritation in the airways is still reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
Irritation in the airways was not reported northwest of Florida in the last week.
